            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: What's new?</b><br /><br />After recalling the hydrogen atom, what do you think Francis William Aston found in the hydrogen atom?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Isotopes\n\nOur understanding of atoms requires that they all have the same number of protons; therefore, the modification found by Francis William Aston in his measurements could not be the addition of a new proton to the nucleus, as that would mean we are talking about a different atom (<htcite0>).\n\nThe measurements of Francis William Aston were confirmed in <htdate0> by Harold C. Urey, F. G. Brickwedde, and G. M. Murphy. Their measurements showed that there is an isotope—atoms that have the same number of protons but a different number of neutrons—of the hydrogen atom that, in addition to the proton, also has a neutron in its nucleus. This isotope is called deuterium (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nIn addition to deuterium, in <htdate1> Marcus Laurence Elwin Oliphant, P. Harteck, and Ernest Rutherford conducted an experiment with deuterium and discovered another hydrogen isotope with two neutrons: tritium (<htcite3>; <htcite4>).",
